      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Actinium is a strongly radioactive, silvery-white, dense metal, glowing with a blue light in the dark. Actinium is the first element in the actinide series, whose properties are similar to the lanthanide series. Its most stable isotopes are </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">227</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Ac, with a half-life of 22 years and </text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">225</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Ac, with a half-life of 10 days. Other actinium isotopes have very short half-lives. Actinium oxidises in air to produce actinium oxide – A</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">c</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. Actinium compounds are most often white, sometimes colourless. Actinium was discovered in 1899 by a French chemist, Andre  Debierne. The name is derived from the Greek word </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fs="i" fa="1" charset="0">aktínos </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">– ray.</text>
   </par>
